commText: Philip Salt and Narine are at the crease. Philip Salt is on strike. Siraj will open the attack
Siraj to Philip Salt, no run, 135.9kph, short of length ball, defended into the off-side
Siraj to Philip Salt, SIX, 134.8kph, wow! Dismissive from Philip Salt. Short of a good length ball angled in and Salt swings it high and over midwicket for an 89m six. Off the mark in style!
Siraj to Philip Salt, FOUR, 134.3kph, Siraj serves width and Philip Salt latches onto it. The batter stays in his crease to flay it over the covers. Reaches the fence in a jiffy
Siraj to Philip Salt, 1 run, 135.1kph, stays leg-side of the ball and guides this length ball towards deep backward point

Siraj to Narine, 1 run, 137.8kph, pitched up, Narine moves leg-side and jams the drive to the right of mid-off. A direct-hit at the bowler's end would have resulted in Narine getting run-out for the second time in as many innings. Faf misses the target and even the bowler running towards the sticks fails to catch it cleanly

Siraj to Philip Salt, SIX, 105.8kph, pace off, Philip Salt waits and thumps it downtown - over long-off for a 77m six. Not quite off the middle of the bat but he's muscled it. 18 runs off the opening over!
Yash Dayal, left-arm fast medium, comes into the attack

Yash Dayal to Narine, leg byes, 1 run, 129.7kph, short of length ball that nips in a bit, Narine misses the flick as he's cramped for room. The ball hits him high on the pad and rolls behind backward point
No slip for Philip Salt
Yash Dayal to Philip Salt, 1 run, 133.9kph, pitched up, no swing, driven to the right of mid-off and Maxwell makes a diving stop
Yash Dayal to Narine, 2 runs, 114.1kph, full delivery, Narine moves leg-side and miscues the drive to the right of mid-off for a brace
Yash Dayal to Narine, 5 wides, five runs gifted away! Banged in way too short that keeps climbing, Narine half-ducks and the keeper has no chance to even get close to it
Yash Dayal to Narine, FOUR, 135.5kph, short of a good length, Narine slightly backs away and slaps it straight of mid-off. Faf dives to his left but to no avail
Third man comes inside the circle now
Yash Dayal to Narine, 1 run, 132.5kph, back of a length, width offered, cut to the right of extra cover where Green makes a tumbling stop
Yash Dayal to Philip Salt, no run, 129.7kph, probing zone. Short of a good length marginally outside off, Salt tentatively pokes from the crease and the ball whizzes past the outside edge
Alzarri Joseph, right-arm fast medium, comes into the attack

Alzarri Joseph to Narine, 2 runs, 142.9kph, Narine backs away to thump this short of length ball over straight mid-off. The bat turns at the point of impact and hence the timing isn't spot-on. Mid-off runs back and flicks it back into play to save a couple of runs
Alzarri Joseph to Narine, no run, 146.6kph, banged in short wide of off, Narine lets it pass
Alzarri Joseph to Narine, no run, 150.4kph! Too quick. Narine backs away to carve this over the off-side but gets beaten. Pace and bounce for Joseph and Anuj Rawat leaps to catch it

Alzarri Joseph to Narine, SIX, 147.4kph, excellent response from Narine! Joseph goes fuller, Narine moves leg-side, clears his front leg and clobbers it straight down the ground for a 91m six. That's come off the middle of the bat
Alzarri Joseph to Narine, no run, 141.4kph, shortish ball with no room on offer, Narine miscues the pull back to the bowler

Alzarri Joseph to Narine, SIX, 139.6kph, Maxwell runs back from mid-on but can only watch the ball go over the rope. Narine expects another short ball and he gets one. Moves leg-side to pull and hasn't got it anywhere close to the middle of the bat. But the ball still has the wings to go all the way. 14 runs off the over!
RCB under the pump!
Yash Dayal to Philip Salt, no run, 131.3kph, short of length ball, Salt miscues the pull to the right of the bowler

Yash Dayal to Philip Salt, no run, 107.3kph, slower ball, full and outside off, Salt clears his front leg to swing it out of the ground. He's early into his shot and gets a thick inside edge. Dayal stops it in his followthrough

Yash Dayal to Philip Salt, FOUR, 136.3kph, excellent placement! Short of a good length marginally outside off and Salt manages to pierce the gap between backward point and short third man with a superb cut shot. 50 up for KKR in 21 balls!
Yash Dayal to Philip Salt, 2 runs, 137.5kph, swung hard across the line, miscued over wide mid-on for a couple more
Yash Dayal to Philip Salt, no run, 136.9kph, back of a length, hurriedly pulled to midwicket
Yash Dayal to Philip Salt, 1 run, 107.2kph, slow, full and wide of off, Salt throws his arms at it and slices it towards deep point. Joseph comes in and takes it on the bounce
STAT: This is just the fourth 50-plus opening stand for KKR in the IPL since 2022. Every other team has had five or more in the period, RCB leading the way with 13.
Mohammed Siraj [1.0-0-18-0] is back into the attack
Siraj to Philip Salt, 1 run, 134.4kph, in-slanting back of a length ball, Salt swivels to pull and the ball dies down on the leg-side off his glove

Siraj to Narine, 1 run, 132.3kph, short ball, Narine takes his eyes off the ball but doesn't drop his bat as he pulls out from playing the pull shot. The ball hits the bottom part of the bat and rolls to square leg
Siraj to Philip Salt, 1 run, pace off, shortened length and wide of off, Salt slaps it towards mid-off off the bottom part of the bat
Siraj to Narine, no run, 140.2kph, banged in short, Narine fails to make contact with his pull shot as the ball flies over his blade
Siraj to Narine, SIX, 118.4kph, slower ball, leg-lined from a short of length, Narine spots it. Clears his front leg and swings it over deep backward square leg for a 69m six
Siraj to Narine, 2 runs, 144kph, stays leg-side of the ball and slaps the cut to the right of extra cover where Kohli takes pace off the ball with a dive
Yash Dayal to Philip Salt, 1 run, 135.5kph, fullish outside off from over the wicket and Salt drills it to deep point's right

Yash Dayal to Narine, FOUR, edged and four! 106.9kph, slower ball into the wicket, Narine swings early for a pull and gets a top-edge. Short third man turns around and dives but the ball is out of his reach. Runs away to the fence as well

Yash Dayal to Narine, SIX, Narine is dealing in boundaries. Banged in short by Yash Dayal, decent height as well, Narine has picked the length to pummel it over deep midwicket with a ferocious pull shot. Ravi Shastri, on air, says that Dayal gets his second warning for running on the danger area
Yash Dayal to Narine, SIX, slot ball and punished! Back of the hand slower, full and right in the batter's arc. Narine gets under it and bludgeons it downtown. Clean strike
Yash Dayal to Narine, leg byes, FOUR, 136.1kph, Dayal strayd onto the pads, Narine misses the flick and the ball brushes his thigh pad before running away to the fine leg fence
Yash Dayal to Narine, no run, 137.9kph, full on middle and leg, flicked to midwicket. Phew! A 21-run over to end a power-packed powerplay! RCB take the timeout
Highest powerplay scores for KKR in the IPL 105/0 vs RCB, Bengaluru, 2017 85/0 vs RCB, Bengaluru, 2024 76/1 vs PBKS, Kolkata, 2017 73/0 vs GL, Rajkot, 2017
Powerplay summary -- Narine, Salt come out swinging -- RCB pacers taken to the cleaners -- KKR reach 50 in 3.3 overs -- Dayal goes for 37 in 3, Siraj 29 in 2
Mayank Dagar, Left arm orthodox, comes into the attack
Mayank Dagar to Philip Salt, 1 run, 95.1kph, round the wicket, flat ball from a short of length, pulled to deep midwicket
Mayank Dagar to Narine, no run, 93.4kph, away-dart outside off, Narine misses the cut
Mayank Dagar to Narine, THATS OUT!! Bowled!!

Mayank Dagar to Narine, out Bowled!! Mayank Dagar strikes and the crowd find their voice! 101.8kph, yorker, Narine fails to bring his bat down in time and the ball crashes into the base of the off-stump. Dagar is pumped up! No fifty for Narine but he's put his team in pole position. Narine b Mayank Dagar 47(22) [4s-2 6s-5]
Venkatesh Iyer, left handed bat, comes to the crease
Mayank Dagar to Venkatesh Iyer, no run, flat again, middle-stump line on a good length, blunted into the on-side

Mayank Dagar to Venkatesh Iyer, 2 runs, 91.5kph, Venkatesh Iyer comes down the track in an attempt to slog over midwicket, the bottom hand comes off the bat handle and he ends up slicing it in the air over extra cover off the outer edge. Fortunately for him, it falls in no-man's land
Mayank Dagar to Venkatesh Iyer, 1 run, full around leg and Venkatesh Iyer knocks it towards long-on
Vijaykumar Vyshak, right-arm medium, comes into the attack
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Venkatesh Iyer, 1 run, 113.8kph, slower ball on a short of length, Venkatesh Iyer waits and bunts it down the ground. The ball came slower than the batter expected
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Philip Salt, 1 run, 115.2kph, pace off again, chopped towards point
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Venkatesh Iyer, 1 run, 136.3kph, back of a length ball on the pads, Venkatesh Iyer walks across and jabs it through backward square leg
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Philip Salt, no run, 122.9kph, slower ball into the deck outside off, Salt is early into his pull and fails to make contact. The ball goes underneath his swinging blade
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Philip Salt, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Vijaykumar Vyshak to Philip Salt, out Caught by Green!! KKR lose both their openers in quick succession. 136.2kph, in-slanting back of a length ball, Salt pulls hard and flat but picks out the man in the deep. Green moves to his left from deep square leg and completes the catch. The RCB players are elated. Philip Salt c Green b Vijaykumar Vyshak 30(20) [4s-2 6s-2]
Shreyas Iyer, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, 133.8kph, shortish outside off, Shreyas Iyer runs it down to third man to get off the mark
Mayank Dagar to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, 89.3kph, bit of flight, full in length and Shreyas Iyer eases the drive to long-off
Mayank Dagar to Venkatesh Iyer, no run, 91kph, away-dart outside off, Venkatesh Iyer flashes hard for a cut and misses

Mayank Dagar to Venkatesh Iyer, leg byes, 2 runs, 102.2kph, darted full, Venkatesh Iyer walks across to slogsweep and misses. The ball rolls to fine leg off his pad. Half an appeal for lbw but that pitched outside leg
Mayank Dagar to Venkatesh Iyer, SIX, boom! That's a biggie. Dances down the track, gets close to the pitch of the ball and clobbers it high and over deep midwicket for a monstrous six
Venkatesh Iyer tries to reverse-hit, Dagar sees that and doesn't release the ball
Mayank Dagar to Venkatesh Iyer, 1 run, 87.1kph, Venkatesh skips down the track to flick to square leg
Mayank Dagar to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, 89.9kph, opens the bat-face and push-drives with the spin wide of cover

KKR’s opening partnerships in the IPL since 2022 At Chinnaswamy 83 (9.2 overs) - Jason Roy & N Jagadeesan, 2023 86 (6.3 overs) - Phil Salt & Sunil Narine, 2024 Avg: 84.5, RR: 10.68 At other venues Innings: 28 Runs: 478 Avg: 17.07 RR: 7.22 50s: 2

Vijaykumar Vyshak to Shreyas Iyer, no run, well-directed bouncer! It's a good ploy against Shreyas Iyer. The KKR captain is early into his pull and gets hit on the elbow. The physio runs in but Shreyas informs him that it didn't hit his helmet
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Shreyas Iyer, no run, 117.1kph, slower ball on a back of a length, Shreyas Iyer defends

Vijaykumar Vyshak to Shreyas Iyer, 2 runs, 115.3kph, slow, full and wide of off, Shreyas Iyer plays an aerial drive over extra cover. Joseph over-runs to his right but does well to recover and stop it

Vijaykumar Vyshak to Shreyas Iyer, FOUR, dropped! 137.5kph, short ball slanted in on leg, Shreyas Iyer swivels and plays an unconvincing pull shot , Dayal runs in from deep backward square leg, gets low and puts down the chance and lets the ball go past him. A great effort from Green to run across to his right, slide and stop it from hitting the fence, but his knee was in contact with the rope while doing so
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Shreyas Iyer, no run, bumper, head-high and Shreyas Iyer lets it go through to the keeper
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Shreyas Iyer, 2 runs, pace off and full in length, Shreyas Iyer takes the aerial route but mishits over extra cover. Two fieders run back but the ball is out of their reach
Sunil Narine vs RCB in the IPL Inns: 11 Runs: 279 Avg: 31 SR: 195.10 50s: 2 HS: 54 vs other teams Inns: 87 Runs: 816 Avg: 11.83 SR: 151.67 50s: 2 HS: 75
Alzarri Joseph [1.0-0-14-0] is back into the attack
Alzarri Joseph to Venkatesh Iyer, no run, 145kph, short of length delivery outside off, Venkatesh goes flat-batted and slaps it to mid-off
Alzarri Joseph to Venkatesh Iyer, SIX, bludgeoned into the crowd! Short of length on leg, slower one that sits up for Venkatesh as he advances, and he swats it over midwicket with a lot of power

Alzarri Joseph to Venkatesh Iyer, FOUR, such an ordinary effort in the deep! It's Dayal again. Short of length outside off, Venkatesh waits on it, cuts nicely past backward point but it should've been cut off at deep third. Wasn't easy. Dayal had to charge to his left and put in a slide. But weirdly, he went with his legs first, and his body trailing behnd. It sneaks through for four
Alzarri Joseph to Venkatesh Iyer, no run, sharp bouncer from Joseph, it's well directed and Venkatesh ducks quickly to evade

Alzarri Joseph to Venkatesh Iyer, SIX, pulled away for six, and Venkatesh is in pain after playing that shot. Physio runs out to check on him. Short of length delivery straying down leg, Venkatesh spins on his toes and pulls nicely over short fine. But he hurt himself while twisting in that manner
Venkatesh ready to go again after a bit of a delay

Alzarri Joseph to Venkatesh Iyer, FOUR, short again from Joseph, and it disappears to the boundary again! Venkatesh gets lucky this time. The ball gets big on him as he goes for the pull, but it flies off a thick top-edge over the keeper
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, back of a length around the waist, slower one, Shreyas clips it behind square
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Venkatesh Iyer, 1 run, back of a length outside off, slower one, and Venkatesh dabs it to backward point for a quick single
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, short of length around the chest, slower one, Shreyas gently pulls through square leg
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Venkatesh Iyer, 1 run, length ball outside off, Venkatesh steps out and drives hard to long-off
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, full toss on middle and leg, Shreyas drives to long-on
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Venkatesh Iyer, no run, slower bouncer outside off, Venkatesh goes for an upper-cut but misses. He's unhappy that it's not called wide for height
Cameron Green, right-arm medium, comes into the attack
Green to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, 134kph full ball on the pads, Shreyas flicks it to long-on
Green to Venkatesh Iyer, no run, 131kph back of a length outside off, Venkatesh looks to cut but is beaten
Green to Venkatesh Iyer, FOUR, full outside off, Venkatesh dances down and carves it over extra cover. Doing it easy at the moment. Fifty partnership is up off just 28 balls
Green to Venkatesh Iyer, no run, back of a length on off, 130kph, Venkatesh looks to pull but is very late on it. Mistimes it to mid-off
Green to Venkatesh Iyer, 1 run, 133kph length ball angled in on middle and leg, cramps Venkatesh for room as he advances and he mistimes the slog to deep midwicket
Green to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, length ball straying on the pads, Shreyas clips it to deep midwicket

Highlights (Overs 7-13) -- 59/2 -- Dagar cleans up the dangerous Narine -- Salt falls to Vyshak in the following over -- Shreyas troubled by the short ball; Dayal drops him on 5 -- Joseph to Venkatesh Iyer: 0 6 4 0 6 4 -- Vyshak bowls an economical over -- Fifty partnership between Venkatesh & Shreyas
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, short of length outside off, Shreyas cuts to deep point
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Venkatesh Iyer, 1 run, slower one floated up outside off, Venkatesh drives hard to long-off
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, good bouncer at the head, Shreyas swivels across and gently pulls to fine leg
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Venkatesh Iyer, 1 run, 138kph, very full on off, Venkatesh drills it to long-on
Vijaykumar Vyshak to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, slower dipping yorker on off, Shreyas squeezes it to point for a quick single. Misfield from Virat

Vijaykumar Vyshak to Venkatesh Iyer, 1 run, length ball on middle and leg, Venkatesh mistimes the pull to deep midwicket. Vyshak bowls out with figures of 1/23. Has stood out in an attack which has been taken to the cleaners
Mohammed Siraj [2.0-0-29-0] is back into the attack
Siraj to Venkatesh Iyer, SIX, short of length at the body, slower one at 127kph, and it's pummeled over square leg! Sat up around the chest for Venkatesh who nailed the pull shot into the crowd
Siraj to Venkatesh Iyer, wide, 140kph length ball down leg, Venkatesh misses and groans in frustration
Siraj to Venkatesh Iyer, 1 run, pitched up on off, Venkatesh hammers it to long-off
Siraj to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, back of a length on off, Shreyas pulls it gently wide of long-on
Siraj to Venkatesh Iyer, wide, slower bouncer outside off, Venkatesh tries to reach it but can't. It's called a wide for height
Siraj to Venkatesh Iyer, no run, back of a length outside off, Venkatesh cuts to backward point where Kohli fields
Siraj to Venkatesh Iyer, 1 run, Venkatesh advances, gets a sharp short ball and swats it to long-on. Gets a single which takes him to fifty. He removes his helmet and blows a kiss towards the dugout

Siraj to Shreyas Iyer, SIX, oh lovely timing from Shreyas! Full delivery at the pads, and it's met with a delightful pick-up shot as Shreyas whips it over wide long-on. It goes skimming over the ropes
Yash Dayal [3.0-0-37-0] is back into the attack
Yash Dayal to Venkatesh Iyer, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Yash Dayal to Venkatesh Iyer, out Caught by Kohli!! Venkatesh holes out in the deep! Slower length ball outside off, he looks to slog but doesn't get hold of it. Finds Kohli at the midwicket boundary and he's not going to drop that. Venkatesh Iyer c Kohli b Yash Dayal 50(30) [4s-3 6s-4]

Timeout! Just 16 more needed for KKR, and they've got plenty of time to do it in. The way they've gone about this innings has completely silenced the crowd. Most of them still haven't left the ground though.
Most catches as a fielder in the IPL 109 - Suresh Raina 109 - Virat Kohli 103 - Kieron Pollard 99 - Rohit Sharma 97 - Ravindra Jadeja
Rinku Singh, left handed bat, comes to the crease
Yash Dayal to Rinku Singh, 1 run, short of length into the body, Rinku pulls it in the air and it goes to fine leg on the bounce
Yash Dayal to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, 133kph, length ball slanted away outside off, Shreyas drives nicely to sweeper cover
Yash Dayal to Rinku Singh, wide, slower bouncer that loops over Rinku's head and is called wide
Yash Dayal to Rinku Singh, 1 run, 134kph, back of a length delivery on middle and leg, Rinku mistimes the pull in the air but it falls short of deep backward square

Yash Dayal to Shreyas Iyer, FOUR, half-stop from the fielder, but it still runs away to the boundary. Back of a length outside off, Shreyas waits on it and dabs it to the right of short third. Fielder gets a hand diving across but in vain
Yash Dayal to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, slower length ball on middle, Shreyas knocks it to long-on
Mayank Dagar [2.0-0-13-1] is back into the attack
Mayank Dagar to Shreyas Iyer, 1 run, flat on middle, back of a length, Shreyas punches it from the crease to long-off
Mayank Dagar to Rinku Singh, 2 runs, 101.2kph, full ball fired into the pads, Rinku flicks wide of long-on and they get back for two
Mayank Dagar to Rinku Singh, no run, flat outside off, Rinku cuts wide of backward point who makes a diving stop
Mayank Dagar to Rinku Singh, 1 run, 100kph, fired in full on middle, Rinku clears the front leg and lofts it down the ground. Goes on the bounce to the fielder at long-off who was quite straight

Mayank Dagar to Shreyas Iyer, SIX, Shreyas finishes it off, and KKR become the first team to win away from home this season! Has taken 10 matches for that to happen. Slightly short at the stumps, and it's enough for Shreyas who pulls it over the midwicket boundary

22:48 Local Time, 17:18 GMT, 22:48 IST: Not only do KKR become the first team to win away from home this season, but they also extend their winning run at this venue. They've remained unbeaten here since 2015, and today was a particularly emphatic performance from the men in purple. 182 looked like a decent total from the hosts, given that the pitch was on the slower side and it seemed difficult to hit against the older ball. RCB's scoring rate dropped after the powerplay, and the KKR bowlers used their cutters really well, especially the likes of Russell and Harshit Rana. However, when it came to the chase, KKR didn't have to worry too much about the scoring rate against the older ball because Sunil Narine and Phil Salt pretty much killed the game in the powerplay itself. The two of them came out swinging and put RCB's pacers to the sword, with 85 coming off the first six overs. If the game wasn't done there, then it was certainly done when Venkatesh Iyer backed up the openers with a quickfire fifty which completely shut the door on the home team, leaving the crowd dead silent. All in all, it was a night to forget for RCB. Hang around, we'll have the presentations shortly.

Faf du Plessis: Strange one, first innings we thought that the wicket was very two-paced, you could see that when the guys bowled the cutters, back of a length, the guys really struggled. We thought it was a decent score knowing that it gets a little bit easier in the evening, there was a little bit of dew that came in. Looking at the way we batted in the first innings, even if you have someone in there, Virat was struggling to hit the ball just because there was lack of pace and the two-paceness. (Could anything have done differently in the powerplay with the ball?) You can always know after the game, we can say perhaps try one or two things but the way the two of them (Narine and Slat) were striking the ball, some really good batting there, they put pressure on our bowlers. They hit strong cricket shots and pretty much took the game away. With Narine there, you can't really go to spin, you want to use pace upfront. That's also a really good match-up for Salt and the way he plays. They were excellent, really broke the game in the first six overs. We've tried the spinning options with Maxi, the finger-spinners seem be be effective here, but at night there wasn't too much spin, With left-hand, right-hand combination, it's one of those things, you can bowl a spinner. But as you saw when Venky was playing against the left-arm spinner, you feel like it's an easy hit on a small boundary to hit with the spin. Ideally you want someone who can spin the ball both ways but with the set-up of our team tonight, we didn't have that option. (On Vyshak) Very good, he hasn't had opportunities. We had a look in the first innings and we thought about bringing in Karn Sharma. But we felt someone who could bowl really good slower balls is probably the most difficult bowler to face on this pitch. Dre Russ probably bowled 80% of his balls cutters. We took some learnings from that and he was the best bowler of the evening.

Venkatesh Iyer: [on his back] It's just a little jacked up, have to go and have a scan. To be honest, it got better as the game went on, one end in particular, the Pavilion end and credit to Narine, the pressure was off and we had to go and finish the formalities. It was very important to capitalise on the platform laid, the left-arm spinner was bowling and it was my duty to go after the bowling. Also my fiancee is here and I would like to credit her. Vyshak bowled really well, used the change-ups nicely. To face him was a little tough, pace off on that pitch in totality was tough. even when we bowled quick deliveries, it was tough.
KKR have now won five of their last six matches against RCB, they had lost four on the trot before this sequence.
This is KKR’s sixth consecutive win against RCB at the M. Chinnaswamy Stadium since 2016. RCB had a 4-2 win record against the opponent at home between 2008 and 2015.
RCB bowling today \nMayank Dagar & Vijaykumar Vyshak: 2/46 from 6.5 overs (ER: 6.73) \nOthers: 1/133 in 10 overs (ER: 13.3)
Stats courtesy Roshan Gede

Shreyas, KKR captain: Coming here, getting those two sessions of practice, we were in a good shape from the previous game. Coming and hitting few balls, it felt comfortable from within. The way Russell came in and realised the wicket wasn't giving much for bowlers, and went to slower ones, analysing the conditions on the spot was pleasing to the eye. The communication was brilliant. See when Narine comes in to open, he knows he has one job which is to clear the infield. Today we were contemplating whether to start with him or not but he did a brilliant job. From one end, it was good to bat on. From the other end it was two paced. That was the communication we had in the middle and we passed it onto others. Would be spending a day tomorrow in Bangalore, and then go to Vizag. I'm not expecting much at this point of time - it's just the start of the tournament. Want to enjoy each other's success - that's the plan for now.

Sunil Narine, POTM: It's a nice milestone (500 T20s). Hopefully 500 more to come. It's just the self belief and the support staff giving the encouragement. Also the hard work. Powerplay over is the hardest over - just have to let that go and keep it tight. Helps when you win. Players have full freedom to do what they want to do.

RCB were blown away tonight. Barring that hug, KKR were ruthless on the field and have made it two wins in two games. So that's all we have from here. It's a goodbye from Sagar Chawla on behalf of Harish and Abhinand Raghavendran. Goodnight!
